And the wall collapsed …
Here's a quiz for history enthusiasts: 20 years ago, 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4th.
Which one do you remember best, and which one had the greatest consequence for the planet?
a) The bloody repression of Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few answer c).
For the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made headlines, overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarność in the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe – and consequently to the reordering of the post-war international order.
In the coming months, there will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was a moment of glory, symbolic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins remain unclear.
But those who witnessed the collapse of the Eastern Bloc from the start realize that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement for change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader at the helm of Poland, General Jaruzelski, believed that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to handle alone.
Why not turn to the Polish opposition, he thought – if not to find a solution, at least to share the responsibility for the situation?
After six months of bargaining, he concluded a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections, and Solidarność could participate.
Neither the communist leaders (nor Solidarność) ever imagined for a moment that they might lose.
Even in their darkest dreams, they did not imagine being chased out of power.
Yet, that is what happened.
In retrospect, it is astonishing that there were any doubts.
Solidarność campaigned boldly.
A famous poster parodyed for the occasion, one of a classic Western movie, "The Train Will Blow Its Horn Three Times," was very successful: it shows Gary Cooper holding a ballot instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4 was the day of judgment.
On that bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving birth to summer, voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to one final perversity that turned into an involuntary self-degradation.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting candidates of their choice, had to cross out the names of those they did not want - essentially all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere you looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had been waiting for so long, the revenge against December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarność, and threw its leaders in jail.
The revolution by pen!
Wielded with style, the pen that ultimately triumphed over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Certain voters ripped their ballot papers completely, effectively decapitating the old regime with a swift and effective move.
Others savored the moment, perhaps smoking a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "And that apparatchik got rich off our shortages," Pfft!
Pfft!
The communist campaign, however, went almost unnoticed.
In all of Warsaw, only two government candidates took the trouble to put up posters.
Most relied on their monopoly in the media to get their message across: "Vote Lezek, a good communist."
To his credit, the regime acknowledged its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party leaders to tell them: "Our defeat is total," we need to find a political solution."
This meant that he did not want violence or fraud; the communists would have to live with the election results.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us covering Eastern Europe knew that Solidarność was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern Bloc.
The Polish election was extremely encouraging for anticommunists around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what seemed impossible just a few days earlier became suddenly achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began dismantling the fences erected at the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European Home" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts universally acknowledged: "We didn't see it coming."
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom burst forth.
